    "side_effects_description": "The possible side effect of using Erigeron abyssinicus are causing diarrhea due to its purgative properties, inducing vomiting and nausea due to its emetic effects, leading to dehydration as a result of excessive fluid loss, and inducing diarrhea which can exacerbate dehydration. This is because Erigeron abyssinicus is known to contain sesquiterpene lactones, flavonoids, and phenolic acids, which can have gastrointestinal effects when ingested in large amounts. The improper use of Erigeron abyssinicus can lead to an imbalance of fluids in the body, resulting in dehydration and potentially life-threatening complications. If not treated promptly, dehydration can lead to electrolyte imbalances, kidney damage, and even death. Furthermore, inducing vomiting and nausea can lead to electrolyte imbalances and dehydration, especially in individuals with pre-existing medical conditions or those taking certain medications.",
    "uses": "Erigeron abyssinicus, also known as Abyssinian fleabane, has been traditionally used in various cultures for its medicinal properties. The plant is said to have anti-inflammatory and antiseptic properties, which are believed to aid in the treatment of wounds and skin conditions. In some African cultures, the plant is used to treat fever, rheumatism, and other ailments. However, more research is needed to confirm the effectiveness and safety of using Erigeron abyssinicus for medicinal purposes. Further studies are necessary to fully understand the plant's potential health benefits.",
    "taxonomy": "Erigeron abyssinicus is classified within the family Asteraceae, which is a large and diverse group of flowering plants commonly known as the daisy or sunflower family. This family comprises over 23,000 species and is one of the largest and most widespread plant families in the world. The genus Erigeron, to which Erigeron abyssinicus belongs, consists of approximately 70 species of annual and perennial plants. These plants are primarily native to North America, but some species, such as Erigeron abyssinicus, are found in Africa. The classification of Erigeron abyssinicus as a species within the Asteraceae family reflects its evolutionary relationships with other flowering plants.",
    "benefits": "Erigeron abyssinicus, also known as Abyssinian daisy, is a plant that has been traditionally used in medicine for its various health benefits. The plant has been reported to exhibit antioxidant, anti-inflammatory, and antimicrobial properties, which can contribute to its potential health benefits. In traditional medicine, Erigeron abyssinicus is often used to treat respiratory issues, such as bronchitis and coughs, due to its expectorant properties. It is also believed to have antiseptic and anti-fungal properties, which can aid in wound healing and preventing infections. Further research is needed to confirm the extent of its health benefits and potential applications.",
